  "prompt": "What does white smoke from motorcycle exhaust mean?",
  "response": "White smoke from a motorcycle exhaust can indicate a few possible issues:\n\n1. **Condensation**: If the white smoke is mostly visible when you start the bike and dissipates as it warms up, it might simply be condensation. This is more common in colder weather and typically isn't a cause for concern.\n\n2. **Coolant Leak**: White smoke that persists and has a sweet smell could mean that coolant is leaking into the combustion chamber, often due to a blown head gasket or a cracked engine block or cylinder head. This requires immediate attention, as running an engine with a coolant leak can cause serious damage.\n\n3. **Unburned Fuel**: In some cases, white smoke might be caused by unburned fuel, especially if the smoke dissipates quickly. This can be a sign of an overly rich fuel mixture or an issue with the fuel system.\n\n4. **Oil Burn**: While oil burning typically causes blue smoke, sometimes light oil burning can appear white. This can be due to worn piston rings or valve seals, allowing oil to enter the combustion chamber.\n\nIf you notice persistent white smoke, it's a good idea to have your motorcycle inspected by a professional to diagnose and address the issue properly.",
